title: EBNF - Widgets and Attributes

!! HTML Elements and Widgets

The same parser rule ([[html.js|https://github.com/TiddlyWiki/TiddlyWiki5/blob/master/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/html.js]]) handles both plain HTML elements and TiddlyWiki widgets. Widgets are distinguished by the `$` prefix on their tag name. When the parser sees a `$` prefix, the node type is set to the widget name (the tag minus the `$` character); otherwise the node type is `element`.

* HTML: `<div class="foo">content</div>`
* Widget: `<$list filter="[tag[doc]]">content</$list>`
* Self-closing: `<br/>` or `<$set name="x" value="y"/>`

''Block vs inline:'' If the opening tag is followed by a double newline (blank line), the content is parsed in block mode. Otherwise the content is parsed in inline mode. This is what allows widgets to contain block-level content like paragraphs and headings.

The tag name regex allows alphanumeric characters, hyphens, `$`, and dots: `/([a-zA-Z0-9\-\$\.]+)/`

```
HTMLElement   ::= '<' TagName Attributes? ( '/>' | '>' Content '</' TagName '>' )
TagName       ::= '$' WidgetName | HTMLTagName
WidgetName    ::= [a-zA-Z0-9] [a-zA-Z0-9.\-]*
HTMLTagName   ::= [a-zA-Z] [a-zA-Z0-9.\-]*
Content       ::= BlockContent | InlineContent    (* block if double-newline after open tag *)
```

Note: A tag starting with `-` is rejected by `isLegalTag()` for HTML elements (but widgets are always legal).

!! The Attribute System (7 Value Forms)

This is the most complex part of the wikitext syntax. Attributes can appear on HTML elements, widgets, and image syntax. The parser in [[parseutils.js|https://github.com/TiddlyWiki/TiddlyWiki5/blob/master/core/modules/parsers/parseutils.js]] tries each value form in a specific order, taking the first match.

The attribute name allows any character except: `/` whitespace `>` `"` `'` `` ` `` `=`

!!! 1. String Value

`attr="value"` or `attr='value'` or `attr=[[value]]` or `attr="""value"""`

Four quoting styles are supported. The `""".."""` triple-double-quote form allows embedded double quotes and newlines. The `[[...]]` form is familiar from TiddlyWiki link syntax.

Also unquoted: `attr=value` (the value must not contain `/` whitespace `<` `>` `"` `'` `` ` `` `=`).


''Example:'' `<$list filter="[tag[doc]]">`, `<$text text='hello'>`, `<$set name=[[My Variable]]>`
!!! 2. Filtered Value

`attr={{{filter-expression}}}`

The filter is evaluated at runtime. The first result of the filter becomes the attribute value.

''Example:'' `<$text text={{{[tag[doc]first[]]}}}/>`

!!! 3. Indirect Value (Text Reference)

`attr={{tiddler!!field}}`

Looks up a text reference at runtime. The value inside the double braces is a standard TiddlyWiki text reference (e.g., `MyTiddler`, `MyTiddler!!field`, `MyTiddler##index`).

''Example:'' `<$text text={{MyTiddler!!caption}}/>`

!!! 4. Macro/Variable Value

`attr=<<macroname params>>`

Evaluates a macro or variable invocation and uses the result as the attribute value. The macro call syntax inside the angle brackets follows the standard macro invocation syntax.

''Example:'' `<$text text=<<currentTiddler>>/>`

!!! 5. MVV (Multi-Valued Variable) Value

`attr=((varname))`

A variable reference evaluated at runtime. Internally stored as a transclusion node with `isMVV: true`.

''Example:'' `<$text text=((my-variable))/>`

!!! 6. Substituted Value

`attr=` &#96;`text with $(variable)$ substitution`&#96; or `attr=` &#96;&#96;&#96;`multiline text`&#96;&#96;&#96;

Text with `$(varname)$` placeholders that are replaced at runtime. This is a text substitution mechanism, not a filter. The triple-backtick form allows the value to span multiple lines and contain single backticks.

''Example:'' (see Substituted Attributes in Detail below)

!!! 7. Boolean (No Value)

`disabled` alone (without `=`) means the attribute value is `"true"`.

If the parser finds an attribute name followed by `=` but none of the value forms match, it also falls back to `"true"`.

''Example:'' `<$list filter="[tag[doc]]" variable="item" counter="num">` (counter is a boolean-style attribute)

!! Parse Order

The `parseAttribute()` function tries value forms in this specific order after seeing `=`:

# String literal (`"..."`, `'...'`, `[[...]]`, `"""..."""`) -- checked first via `parseStringLiteral()`
# Filtered value (`{{{...}}}`)
# Indirect value (`{{...}}`)
# Macro invocation (`<<...>>`)
# MVV reference (`((...))`) 
# Substituted value (&#96;`...`&#96; or &#96;&#96;&#96;`...`&#96;&#96;&#96;)
# Unquoted value (any run of non-delimiter characters)
# Fallback: value is `"true"`

This ordering matters. For example, `{{{filter}}}` is checked before `{{textref}}`, so there is no ambiguity between filtered and indirect values. Similarly, `(((...)))` would be parsed as MVV wrapping a filter-like expression, not as nested MVV references.

!! Substituted Attributes in Detail

Inside backtick-quoted attribute values, the `$(varname)$` placeholder syntax provides text substitution:

```
<$text text=`Hello $(username)$, you have $(count)$ messages`/>
```

This is a text substitution mechanism, not a filter. The variable name between `$(` and `)$` is looked up at runtime and its value replaces the entire `$(varname)$` token. Multiple placeholders can appear in a single substituted attribute value.

The triple-backtick form allows multiline substituted values:

```
<$text text=```First line with $(var1)$
Second line with $(var2)$```/>
```

!! Design Notes

* The attribute system is arguably the most complex part of wikitext -- 7 value forms, each with its own delimiter syntax.
* All attribute value forms share the same syntax regardless of whether they appear on an HTML element or a widget.
* The parser tries each form in order: string literals first, then filtered, indirect, macro, MVV, substituted, unquoted. The first match wins.
* Attributes can span multiple lines when using `"""..."""` or triple-backtick forms.
* The attribute name regex is deliberately permissive -- it accepts any character not in the delimiter set (`/`, whitespace, `>`, `"`, `'`, &#96;, `=`). This means attribute names like `data-custom` and `$variable` are valid.
* In `html.js`, the `parseTag` function loops calling `parseAttribute` until it returns `null`, collecting all attributes into both an ordered array (`orderedAttributes`) and a name-keyed object (`attributes`). If duplicate attribute names appear, the last one wins in the object, but all are preserved in the ordered array.

!! Combined EBNF

```
(* === HTML Elements and Widgets === *)

HTMLElement     ::= '<' TagName Attributes? ( '/>' | '>' Content '</' TagName '>' )
TagName         ::= '$' WidgetName | HTMLTagName
WidgetName      ::= [a-zA-Z0-9] [a-zA-Z0-9.\-]*
HTMLTagName     ::= [a-zA-Z] [a-zA-Z0-9.\-]*
Content         ::= BlockContent | InlineContent

(* === Attributes === *)

Attributes      ::= ( WS Attribute )*
Attribute       ::= AttrName ( '=' AttrValue )?

AttrName        ::= [^\/\s>"'`=]+

AttrValue       ::= StringLiteral                        (* quoted string *)
                   | '{{{' FilterExpr '}}}'               (* filtered value *)
                   | '{{' TextReference '}}'              (* indirect value *)
                   | '<<' MacroCall '>>'                  (* macro/variable value *)
                   | '((' VarName '))'                    (* MVV variable *)
                   | '```' SubstitutedText '```'          (* substituted, multiline *)
                   | '`' SubstitutedText '`'              (* substituted, single-line *)
                   | UnquotedValue                        (* unquoted string *)

(* === String Literals === *)

StringLiteral   ::= '"""' AnyChar* '"""'                  (* triple-double-quote, lazy match *)
                   | '"' [^"]* '"'                        (* double-quoted *)
                   | "'" [^']* "'"                        (* single-quoted *)
                   | '[[' ( [^\]] | ']' [^\]] )* ']]'    (* double-bracket *)

UnquotedValue   ::= [^\/\s<>"'`=]+

(* === Substitution Placeholders === *)

SubstitutedText ::= ( PlainText | Placeholder )*
Placeholder     ::= '$(' VarName ')$'

(* === Macro Call (inside attribute value) === *)

MacroCall       ::= MacroName ( WS MacroParam )*
MacroParam      ::= ( ParamName ':' )? ParamValue
ParamValue      ::= StringLiteral | UnquotedMacroParam
```

